article.description:
Shawn Marion scored 21 points and grabbed 14
rebounds to help Phoenix beat Denver 107-96 on Saturday night in a
showdown of division leaders and possible playoff preview.
article.headline: Suns win battle of division leaders, top Nuggets
article.linkText: Suns down Nuggets in battle of division leaders

inlines.body:
Nuggets vs. West's Best
Spurs 1-2
Mavericks 1-2
Suns 1-3
Clippers 1-2
TOTALS 4-9

article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Suns beat the Denver Nuggets in a showdown of NBA division leaders, and yet all the talk after the game was about how poorly Phoenix played.
Nuggets vs. West's Best
Spurs 1-2
Mavericks 1-2
Suns 1-3
Clippers 1-2
TOTALS 4-9
They shot only 43.3 percent from the floor, well below their 48.0 percent average, second-best in the NBA. They blew a 14-point second-quarter lead. And they lacked the energy they had two nights earlier, when Amare Stoudemire returned to the lineup after missing the first 66 games with a knee injury. Despite all that the Suns beat Denver, a possible second-round playoff opponent, 107-96. "We weren't really sharp tonight, but I thought we were tough enough to get through it and to put in a winning performance," said Suns guard Steve Nash, whose 21 points matched Shawn Marion for the team high. Marion also added 14 rebounds for his 53rd double-double of the season, matching a career high. With the victory, the Pacific Division-leading Suns moved closer to their 16th playoff berth in 18 years. Phoenix will clinch a spot with one more victory or a loss by New Orleans. Carmelo Anthony scored 28 points and Andre Miller 21 for the Northwest Division-leading Nuggets, whose three-game win streak ended. On Thursday night, Stoudemire scored 20 points in 19 minutes in a 125-108 victory over the woeful Portland Trail Blazers. He wasn't nearly as dominant against Denver, with six points and five rebounds in 17 minutes. "We're still working Amare in," coach Mike D'Antoni said. "His body was dead tonight and didn't have the juice -- probably the adrenaline from last time. "You can't do that every night," D'Antoni said. "It's going to be a process of getting him back, and we talked about it. It's going to be a process. It's natural. We'll limp a little bit sometimes but if we can play like this and win big games while we're rehabbing, that's great." Phoenix and Denver are close to locking up the second and third seeds, respectively, in the Western Conference playoffs. If they avoid first-round upsets, the Suns and Nuggets would meet in the second round. That's why this game loomed large. By winning for the third time in the four-game season series, the Suns hoped to instill doubt in the Nuggets heading into the postseason. "They've had our number for the last year and a half," Denver forward Carmelo Anthony said. "They're probably the only team that has our number. I don't believe I'm saying this but it's true." Boris Diaw, a 6-foot-8 center, had 13 assists to lead Phoenix in that category for the second game in a row. He also had 13 points, giving him his 14th double-double of the season. Diaw, acquired from Atlanta as part of the Joe Johnson deal, had only one double-double in two seasons with the Hawks. Diaw's assists came on a night that Nash, the league's assist leader, had as many rebounds (6) as assists. "Boris is a terrific passer," Nash said. "I pass to him and he passes to the shooter and it's a good combination. I like it." Phoenix looked like it was going to coast when it outscored the Nuggets 12-2 to open the second quarter, taking a 14-point lead. But Denver rallied and led 74-72 with 2:30 to go in the third quarter when the Suns erupted, reeling off a 13-1 run to take an 85-75 lead 93 seconds into the fourth quarter. The Suns outscored Denver 28-21 in the final period, hitting 5-of-8 three-pointers. "Things aren't going to go well every night," Nash said. "But if you have the right attitude and you're active and you play with a lot of heart and play together, you make up for a lot."

Game notes
The Suns will put Kurt Thomas on the playoff roster, coach Mike D'Antoni said. Thomas, who is out six to eight weeks with a stress fracture in his right foot, may not be available until the second round. ... Denver forward Kenyon Martin was back in the lineup Saturday night after missing one game with a left knee bruise. ...The Suns leave Sunday for a seven-day, five-game East Coast trip that ends with a game at Detroit on April 2. ... Nash, who is averaging 19.7 points and 10.7 assists per game, needs to raise his scoring average .3 points to become the first NBA player in 13 years to average at least 20 points and 10 assists in a single season. The last was former Golden State guard Tim Hardaway in 1992-93.
